      "lotl": {
        "label": "What's Going On With the Leafs",
        "body": "The puck dropped on Toronto's regular-season epitaph last night, a <strong>6-5 gut-punch loss to Dallas</strong> in the home finale that encapsulated every Leafs heartbreak &mdash; five goals tallied, yet leaking oil at both ends like a '79 Cadillac. Sitting at 42-28-12, they've clawed into third in the Atlantic, two points clear of Tampa but with the conference's tiebreaker woes gnawing like an old playoff scar. Auston Matthews, invisible for weeks amid whispers of a nagging hammy, mustered a goal but vanished when the Stars' chaos hit; meanwhile, Woll's crease crumbled under six Dallas tallies, exposing the goaltending roulette that's doomed them since Belfour bolted. Knies flashed fire with two helpers, but this crew's streak-snapping skid &mdash; three losses in four &mdash; screams regression, not redemption. The real war begins Friday: <strong>playoff opener versus Boston</strong>, where Matthews needs to erupt or it's Cup dreams in the dustbin again.",
        "updated": "Updated April 15, 2026"
      },
