      "lotl": {
        "label": "What's Going On With the Jays",
        "body": "The Blue Jays staggered into Milwaukee like a fighter punch-drunk after four straight series losses, their 7-9 record a stubborn anchor in the AL East muck. <strong>Vladimir Guerrero Jr. torched the last 10 games with 13 hits and a .342/.419/.526 slash</strong>, dragging the offense from the abyss &mdash; three homers from Daulton Varsho helped, too, amid 31 extra-base hits that fueled a .376 slugging surge. But the bats cooled too often, averaging just 8.2 hits per tilt, leaving pitchers exposed in a division where every misstep bites. No major injuries cripple the roster, yet the skid screams urgency; they've won just enough to stay scrappy, not dominant. Tonight, Dylan Cease (0-0) toes the rubber against a Brewers club reeling from six straight defeats &mdash; their house of pain could be Toronto's salve. <strong>If the Jays sweep this interleague set, they flip the script on a lost April</strong>; otherwise, it's back to the trade-rumor grinder.",
        "updated": "Updated April 15, 2026"
      },
